{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:58:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:58:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13915"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13915"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.02,0.67,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6534"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53405"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"278"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2564"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up of his recently diagnosed obstructive sleep apnea (OSA). He underwent a sleep study two weeks ago, which revealed an apnea-hypopnea index (AHI) of 35 events per hour, consistent with severe OSA. During the study, his oxygen saturation dropped to 82% multiple times overnight. He reports loud snoring, frequent nocturnal awakenings, and daytime sleepiness. His medical history includes hypertension and obesity with a BMI of 34 kg/m2. He takes amlodipine and lisinopril for hypertension. His thyroid function tests are normal. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 78/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Oropharyngeal examination reveals a Mallampati score of 3.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment for this patient\u0027s OSA?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uvulopalatopharyngoplasty","Nocturnal oxygen therapy","Mandibular advancement device","Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) therapy","Dietary modification and exercise program"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate first-line treatment for this patient with severe obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) is \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. CPAP is considered the gold standard treatment for moderate to severe OSA, as it effectively maintains airway patency during sleep, reducing apneas and hypopneas. It has been shown to improve sleep quality, reduce daytime sleepiness, and potentially lower cardiovascular risk associated with untreated OSA. The significant overnight desaturations to 82% further support the need for immediate effective therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe severity of OSA is determined by the apnea-hypopnea index (AHI), which represents the number of apneas and hypopneas per hour of sleep. An AHI of 5-14 events per hour indicates mild OSA, 15-30 events per hour indicates moderate OSA, and \u003E30 events per hour indicates severe OSA. This patient\u0027s AHI of 35 events per hour clearly indicates severe OSA, warranting CPAP as the first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Edietary modification and exercise program\u003C/strong\u003E are important adjunctive therapies for OSA, especially in obese patients, they are not sufficient as primary treatment for severe OSA. Weight loss can improve OSA severity, but it takes time and may not fully resolve the condition, particularly in severe cases. However, weight loss strategies should be encouraged alongside CPAP therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENocturnal oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not recommended for OSA treatment. While it may improve oxygen saturation, it does not address the underlying problem of airway obstruction and can potentially prolong apneas by delaying arousal responses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMandibular advancement devices\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective for mild to moderate OSA but are generally less effective than CPAP for severe OSA. They may be considered as an alternative if the patient cannot tolerate CPAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUvulopalatopharyngoplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical option that may be considered in select cases of OSA, typically when conservative measures have failed. However, it is not recommended as a first-line treatment, especially before a trial of CPAP therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) is the first-line treatment for moderate to severe obstructive sleep apnea (OSA).","Weight loss is an important adjunctive therapy for OSA but is not the primary treatment for moderate to severe cases.","Nocturnal oxygen therapy alone is not recommended for the treatment of OSA as it does not address the underlying airway obstruction.","An apnea-hypopnea index (AHI) of 15-30 events per hour indicates moderate OSA, while an AHI \u003E30 events per hour indicates severe OSA."],"references":["Spicuzza L, Caruso D, Di Maria G. Obstructive sleep apnoea syndrome and its management. Ther Adv Chronic Dis. 2015 Sep;6(5):273\u201385. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4549693/","Australian Journal of General Practice [Internet]. [cited 2024 Jul 30]. Current management of adult OSA. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/april/current-management-of-adult-osa"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53405"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13915"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53405"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T08:28:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T08:31:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6534"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67940"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"